Our equipment has sustained serious damage as result of a recent meteor shower and is in need of repairs.

localization.Description_FAQ_ContractBlock: A Contract block lets you set up your own contracts for other players to complete. You can also accept contracts from Trading stations.
localization.Description_FAQ_Contracts: Contracts can be accepted trough contract blocks and are a good income of space credit. They can be found at trading stations or from other players with contract blocks.
localization.Description_FAQ_SafeZoneBlock: The safe zone block projects a configurable zone to protect your base. The safe zone block requires power and zone chips to function. Zone chips can be bought from trading stations.
localization.Description_FAQ_SpaceCredit: Space Credit is the universal currency used to trade with stations and other players. You can withdraw or deposit space credits from store blocks.
localization.Description_FAQ_StoreBlock: You can use a store block to trade with players or other factions. Trading can be done from ship inventories when using connectors with trade functions enabled.
localization.Description_FAQ_TradeStations: Trade stations can spawn on planets, moons in orbit or in deep space. Depending on what faction owns the trade station it can sell Ores, components, amunitions, fuel and ships and let you do contracts for them.
localization.Description_FAQ_Trading: You can trade with players and stations using Store blocks. Trading with players can be done directly by pressing F3.

localization.Description_ControlSeat: The control seat is a cockpit block for small and large grids that allows you to control grids. It is highly comfortable but does not supply oxygen.
localization.Description_BlockGroup_DeadBodies: The remains of unfortunate engineers. They can contain loot for others to find.
localization.Description_DeadEngineer: The remains of an unfortunate engineer.
localization.Description_Gate: Gates are large reinforced doors for hallways, entrances, or small hangars. Gates are also air-tight and capable of keeping atmosphere inside.
localization.Description_SciFiWall: Sci-Fi Walls have 6 different sides that can be used to improve your interior design.
localization.DisplayName_BlockGroup_LCDGroupSOTF: Very Large LCD Panels from the Sparks Of the Future pack.
localization.Description_NeonTubes: Neon Tubes are decorative blocks that can be built in all colors.
localization.Description_FAQ_FrostbitePack: The Frostbite Pack includes a new scenario and four new blocks: Antenna Dish, Dead Engineers, Gate and the Offset Door. Additionally, this DLC features the Frozen Armor Skin and LCD Posters.
localization.Description_AntennaDish:
Antennas can be used to broadcast positions, messages HUD markers and allows grids to be accessed or controlled from a distance.

Antennas need to be able to send and receive, so make sure two antennas always overlap each other's position.
localization.Description_OffsetDoor: Doors can seal off interiors and make them air tight while still allowing access for the player.

localization.Description_BarCounter: With a decorative bar counter block you can create a place to serve drinks and share stories of heroism and tragedy.
localization.Description_TextBlocks: Letters, numbers and symbol blocks allow you to build text and indications onto your ships and structures.
localization.Description_FAQ_SOTFPack: The Sparks Of The Future Pack comes with several new blocks like Neon Tubes, a small grid door and a unique button panels. It also comes with several new character animations and armor skins.
localization.Description_FAQ_Weather: There are unique weather systems on every planet that can affect sunlight, wind, oxygen and temperature. Lightning can be dangerous and damage your structures but prioritizes some blocks. Weather can be disabled in world settings.
localization.ScreenDebugAdminMenu_RevertBoulderToolti: For Boulder reverting, minimum player distance is: {0} m.
localization.Description_ExhaustPipe: The Exhaust Pipe emits particles like smoke and fire to decorate vehicles and structures.
localization.Description_BuggyCockpit: The Buggy Cockpit is similar to the rover cockpit but with a roll cage to keep you safe. Please keep hands and feet inside.
localization.Description_RoverCockpit: The Rover Cockpit is a compact cockpit designed for rovers but works just as well for small ships or large small grid interiors.
localization.Description_OffsetLight: The Offset Light and Offset Spotlight function the same as regular lights and can be used to illuminate dark areas.
localization.Description_BarredWindow: Barred windows have the same integrity as glass windows but are not air tight. Great for keeping big spiders outside.
localization.Description_StorageShelf: Storage Shelves can be used to store components and make your hangar or garage look messy and productive.
localization.Description_FAQ_ScrapRacePack: The Wasteland Pack includes a new multiplayer scenario and several new blocks like the Off Road wheels, Car lights, Buggy cockpit, Viewport Blocks and the Exhaust Pipe. Additionally, this DLC features several new armour and player skins like the Heavy Rust Armor Skin, Concrete Armor skin and the Scavenger character skin.
localization.Description_ViewPort: Viewports are available in the Wasteland Pack. They are windows that fit flush with armour blocks and combine easily with desks and kitchens.
localization.Description_WeaponRack: The Weapon Rack stores weapons and ammunition for quick access.
localization.PublishBlueprint_Question: Do you want to publish this blueprint?

localization.TerminalTab_Factions_LeaveToolTip_Balanc: You cannot leave factions when autobalancing is enabled
localization.Description_SemiAutoPistol: The S-10 standard issue sidearm. Built for use in a hostile environment: Simple, reliable, dependable.
localization.Description_FireCover: Fire Covers provide cover in interiors or can be used to prevent players from walking off ledges.
localization.Description_Embrasure: The Embrasure provides cover while allowing you to keep up the pressure on your enemies.
localization.Description_TargetDummy: The Target Dummy block allows you to hone your skills with handheld weaponry or test their mechanics. You can set them up to perform actions when hit or destroyed. The Target Dummy requires steel plates to repair itself.

localization.Description_BasicHandHeldLauncher: Shoulder fired rocket ordinance. Launches a rocket propelled anti-vehicle projectile.
localization.Description_AdvancedHandHeldLauncher: Building on the reliable design of the RO-1 the PRO-1 provides a number of battlefield improvements, including a precision scope.
localization.Description_ElitePistol: An S-10 variant, the E model sidearm features a modified “feather” trigger and boasts a red dot sight.
localization.Description_FullAutoPistol: A true “next-generation” sidearm. Featuring heat resistant components, a full-auto trigger group, and extended ammo capacity. The S-20A is purpose-built to take it to the next level.

localization.Description_EliteAutomaticRifle: The MR-30E is a modernized and battle-ready version of the well known model 20. The model 30E features 3-round burst-fire, an extended magazine, and a red dot sight.
localization.Description_PreciseAutomaticRifle: The MR-8P is designed for long range engagements. The model 8P makes use of a much heavier barrel to achieve unmatched accuracy and stopping power.
localization.Description_RapidFireAutomaticRifle: The MR-50A enjoys notoriety as the smallest squad support machine gun in modern use.  The model 50A can unleash a withering stream of suppressive fire, at a rate of 550 RPM.

localization.Description_FAQ_CombatMechanics: Various hand-held weapons allow you to defend yourself; ranging from basic pistols useful as a sidearm to advanced rifles for special operations, and even anti-armor launchers. These weapons need to be loaded with the correct magazine. Standing still, crouching and aiming the weapon will increase accuracy and reduce recoil.
localization.Description_FAQ_HandHeldLaunchers: Hand-held launchers provide effective anti-armor capability in a small package. The hand-held launchers need to be loaded with the same rocket munition as their block counterparts.
localization.Description_FAQ_Pistols: Sidearms can be used to defend yourself in a hostile environment. They need to be loaded with the corresponding magazines.
localization.Description_FAQ_Rifles: Rifles are a step up from the basic pistol and other sidearms, do more damage to blocks, and fit specialized roles. They need to be loaded with the corresponding magazines.
localization.Description_FAQ_Warfare1: Warfare 1: Field Engineer features a variety of new blocks like the Half Window, Embrasure, Weapon Rack, and Fire Cover, as well as a new skin and emotes.

localization.Description_BasicMissionBlock:
Type: Task

This can be used for basic, customizable AI tasks. It can follow a player, follow and wander around a home position, or perform autopilot functions.
localization.Description_FlightMovementBlock:
Type: Move

This controls the movement of an AI grid, using available thrusters and gyros. Used in conjunction with other AI type blocks, it will attempt to move the grid to waypoints provided by other AI blocks.

An active Move type block is required to make an AI grid move.
localization.Description_DefensiveCombatBlock:
Type: Combat

This can detect and target lock enemy grids up to 2500m. Additionally, it can be set up to flee to a predetermined location when it has detected an enemy.

When enemies are detected, this block takes priority over any active Task type blocks.
localization.Description_OffensiveCombatBlock:
Type: Combat

This can detect, target lock, and engage enemy grids up to 2500m using customizable attack patterns.

When enemies are detected, this block takes priority over any active Task type blocks.
localization.Description_PathRecorderBlock:
Type: Task

This can record a path and action sequence. This path can be relative to another grid if the reference is set. This path and sequence can then be replayed, provided there is a Move type block available on the grid.
localization.PathRecorderBlock_MinimalDistanceBetween: A waypoint is added when the distance to the last waypoint is greater than this value, and the time since the previous waypoint exceeds the Waypoint Addition Interval value.
localization.DefensiveBlock_SetupActions_Tooltip: The first slot triggers when fleeing, the second slot triggers when it stops fleeing.
localization.BasicMissionBlock_SelectMission_Tooltip:
Follow Home - Allows you to select a home beacon or GPS that the grid should follow.
Can be set up to wander while it is within range.

Follow Player - The grid will follow the player who presses the “Follow Me” button.

Autopilot - Allows the grid to move to GPS locations and patrol/circle between several locations.
Patrol and Circle requires 2 GPS locations!
localization.FollowPlayer_FollowDistance_Tooltip: The grid will try to stay within this distance of the player it is following.
localization.FollowHome_SetHome_Tooltip: Creates a GPS at the current location and selects it as the home position.
localization.FollowHome_MinRange_Tooltip: Set the min range away from the home position. The grid will stay between min and max range.
localization.FollowHome_MaxRange_Tooltip: Set the max range away from the home position. The grid will stay between min and max range.
localization.FollowHome_Wander_Tooltip: If set, the grid will wander to random positions within the min and max range from home.
localization.EventControllerBlock_AgregateEvent_Toolt: The first action is triggered if each block meets the condition. Else, the second action is triggered.
localization.DefensiveCombatBlock_DefendAgainst_Toolt: Which other grids may be a threat?
localization.DefensiveCombatBlock_FleeTo_Tooltip: If this grid flees, it will flee towards the selected waypoint.
localization.DefensiveCombatBlock_FleeTrigger_Tooltip:
When to flee?
Never - This grid never flees.
Always - This grid flees when it detects another grid within 2500m and 
the "defend against" and "With Subsystem" conditions are met.
When being Target Locked - When another grid that meets 
the "Defend against" and "With Subsystem" conditions locks this grid.
When taking damage - When taking damage from any source while a grid that meets 
the "Defend against" and "With Subsystem" is within 2500m.

A value of 180 means the grid will retreat back in the same direction it started the attack run from.
A value of 0 means the retreat will continue in a straight line from the attack run.
